{"questionId":"27764","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p><strong>In this question you will investigate series of the form</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><munderover><mo largeop=\"true\">Σ</mo><mrow><mi>i</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mi>n</mi></munderover><msup><mi>i</mi><mi>q</mi></msup><mo>=</mo><msup><mn>1</mn><mi>q</mi></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mn>2</mn><mi>q</mi></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mn>3</mn><mi>q</mi></msup><mo>+</mo><mo>…</mo><mo>+</mo><msup><mi>n</mi><mi>q</mi></msup></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>where&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>q</mi><mo>∈</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">ℤ</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math></p>\n<p><strong>and use various methods to find polynomials, in terms of</strong> <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold-italic\">n</mi></math>, <strong>for such series.</strong></p>\n<p>When&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>q</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math>, the above series is arithmetic.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Consider the case when <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>q</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The following table gives values of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math> and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><munderover><mo largeop=\"true\">Σ</mo><mrow><mi>i</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mi>n</mi></munderover><msup><mi>i</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math>&nbsp; for&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>3</mn></math>.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:left;padding-left:120px;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/3e1b7b9a05aa669b71ca935ba8a98341d14e241e.png\"></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Hence, find the values of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>6</mn></mfrac><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>166666</mn><mo>…</mo><mo>≈</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>167</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>,&nbsp; &nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>,</p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>333333</mn><mo>…</mo><mo>≈</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>333</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A2</strong></em></p>\n<p><br><strong>Note:</strong> Award <em><strong>A1</strong> </em>if only two of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> are correct.<br>Only award <em><strong>FT</strong></em> if three linear equations, each in&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;are stated in part (b) (ii) or (iii).<br>Award <em><strong>A2FT</strong></em> for their&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>.<br>Award <em><strong>A1FT</strong></em> for their&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"27764","referenceCode":"22N.3.AHL.TZ0.1b.iii","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Hence, find the values of a1, a2 and a3.","paper":"3","level":"HL","questionNumber":"b.iii","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 1—Number and algebra","Topic 1—Number and algebra","AHL 1.16—Solution of systems of linear equations"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}